TRIP COMMENTS: With Jeff Boyd searching for Northern Cardinals along the west bank of the Colorado River south of Vidal Wash.
Coverage: The was at the River.----Other observer: Michael
We observed 2 Northern Cardinals in Vidal Wash. They were adult male and female. The male was bright red with a big crest
column47: and a red bill. The female was pale brownish-gray on its head and back. Its crest was pale red and smaller than the male''s. Its lores were black. Its throat was gray. Its wings and tail were pale red. Its breast was whitish-red and its belly was off-white.

TRIP COMMENTS: The White-winged Doves were brownish-gray with dark malars. The eyes were red surrounded by pale blue feathering. The wing coverts were white and the primaries were black. The breast was paler brown than the back. The belly back to the undertail coverts were gray. The underside of the tail was black basally and clean white distally. The tail was square-shaped. All these markings differ from the Mourning Dove''s.

column47: Habitat: Salt Cedar/Pluchea--Temperature: 75-->95F; Wind: 0-5 mph; Cloud cover: 50-->10%. Other vertebrates noted: Uta stansburiana - 5; Cnemidophorus tigris - 1; Citellus tereticaudus - 1.--Large slat cedars and a few honey mesquites dominated. Lots of doves. Parker 1A is type V salt cedar transect with some screwbean and honey mesquite. Parker 1B is a Pluchea transect but is bounded on all sides by screwbean and salt cedar. The Pluchea is also very sparse in spots and is not as tall as some of the other Pluchea transects.

column47: Habitat: Salt Cedar/Pluchea--Temperature: 75-->95F; Wind: 0-5 mph; Cloud cover: 50-->10%. Other vertebrates noted: Uta stansburiana - 5; Cnemidophorus tigris - 1; Citellus tereticaudus - 1.--Large slat cedars and a few honey mesquites dominated. Lots of doves. Parker 1A is type V salt cedar transect with some screwbean and honey mesquite. Parker 1B is a Pluchea transect but is bounded on all sides by screwbean and salt cedar. The Pluchea is also very sparse in spots and is not as tall as some of the other Pluchea transects.

column48: 1977 rains but doesn't appear to have done so extensively. No significant visible damage. Lycium dormant here (in contrast to the leafed out and flowering plants in the east side washes). Some of the smoke trees had put out a few blossoms that were just opening and Stephanomeria also in bloom.--Ash-throated Flycatchers have vacated these washes now.

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: 55-->65F; Wind: 0-2 mph; Cloud cover: 0%. Other vertebrates noted: Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--From my notes: ""Still pretty sparse up here but all Lycium is exhibiting extended growth from what was noted last month. There are some mistletoe clumps of reasonably large size with very ripe berries. The recent rains have pushed tiny shoots of winter grass in this was as well as those seen yesterday [on Parker 34-36]. There are piles of freshly dropped leaves underneath all fo the ironwoods here though the trees do not show it. Strangely
column48: here as nowhere else I have seen locally
column49: the wash ran as a result of the winter rains. The sand appears wet and saturated still.""

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Lepus californicus - 1; Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--I noted the lack of any member of the sparrow guild and ground feeders - likely because the wash had run and washed all the seeds away. I also noted that I detected higher numbers of verdins and gnatcatchers than the previous month possibly because the birds are pairing up and are more vocal and visible. Also more Phainopeplas though they don't seem to be pairing yet. Some are giving a quiet twittery song.--I noted that this wash appeared to have run water within the last month although the last rain I could remember was on 6 November
column48: one day prior to my last visit to these transects. On that day I had noted  that the wash was quite wet but did not appear to have run. That day in December I was unable to find my footprints from 7 November and
column50: those prints would still have been there. I wondered if there'd been another storm in those mountains since that we'd not noticed in Ehrenberg. Whatever the case
column51: there had to have been some water in the wash as the Lycium in this wash which put out new growth in late September
column52: died back quickly between then and November
column53: but was now putting out much more new growth than it had in September.--Plant notes: Opuntia basillaris; O. rammosissima;Pectis papposa (blooming); Encelia frutescens; Coldenia plicata and Dalea emoryi over by the cliff edge; Atriplex polycarpa (with mature seed); Datura meteloides; Encelia farinosa; Euphorbia polycarpa; Euphorbia sp.; and Asclepias subulata (blooming); Hilaria rigida was found scattered amongst the adjacent creosote flats.

column48: 1977 rains but doesn't appear to have done so extensively. No significant visible damage. This was the only type V desert wash transect due to the size of the taller trees in the wash - the vegetation is very sparse compared to the type VI east side washes. Lycium dormant here (in contrast to the leafed out and flowering plants in the east side washes). Some of the smoke trees had put out a few blossoms that were just opening and Stephanomeria also in bloom.--Ash-throated Flycatchers have vacated these washes now.

column47: Parker 40 and 41 are fairly diverse desert wash transects. Plant diversity much higher than 34/35/36 and 37/38/39 washes. --Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland. column48: also); Lycium brevipes (fruit also); Nicotiana trigonophylla. Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: 55-->65F; Wind: 0-2 mph; Cloud cover: 0%. Other vertebrates noted: Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--From my notes: ""Still pretty sparse up here but all Lycium is exhibiting extended growth from what was noted last month. There are some mistletoe clumps of reasonably large size with very ripe berries. The recent rains have pushed tiny shoots of winter grass in this was as well as those seen yesterday [on Parker 34-36]. There are piles of freshly dropped leaves underneath all fo the ironwoods here though the trees do not show it. Strangely
column48: here as nowhere else I have seen locally
column49: the wash ran as a result of the winter rains. The sand appears wet and saturated still.""

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Lepus californicus - 1; Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--I noted the lack of any member of the sparrow guild and ground feeders - likely because the wash had run and washed all the seeds away. I also noted that I detected higher numbers of verdins and gnatcatchers than the previous month possibly because the birds are pairing up and are more vocal and visible. Also more Phainopeplas though they don't seem to be pairing yet. Some are giving a quiet twittery song.--I noted that this wash appeared to have run water within the last month although the last rain I could remember was on 6 November
column48: one day prior to my last visit to these transects. On that day I had noted  that the wash was quite wet but did not appear to have run. That day in December I was unable to find my footprints from 7 November and
column50: those prints would still have been there. I wondered if there'd been another storm in those mountains since that we'd not noticed in Ehrenberg. Whatever the case
column51: there had to have been some water in the wash as the Lycium in this wash which put out new growth in late September
column52: died back quickly between then and November
column53: but was now putting out much more new growth than it had in September.--Plant notes: Opuntia basillaris; O. rammosissima;Pectis papposa (blooming); Encelia frutescens; Coldenia plicata and Dalea emoryi over by the cliff edge; Atriplex polycarpa (with mature seed); Datura meteloides; Encelia farinosa; Euphorbia polycarpa; Euphorbia sp.; and Asclepias subulata (blooming); Hilaria rigida was found scattered amongst the adjacent creosote flats.

column48: and I began the day looking for Northern Cardinals at the traditional site along the west bank of the Colorado River between Agnes Wilson Road and the mouth of Vidal Wash.  While here
column49: we walked along the ""frontage"" road that traversed a riparian corridor that consisted primarily of tamarisk and mesquite.  Farther from the river the vegetation was more typically desert-like
column50: with Smoke Trees and Palo Verde spaced at a greater interval.  Not surprisingly
column52: which are typically difficult to find when they aren't singing.  It was basically clear with an intermittent
column53: mild (5 knot) breeze
column54: and in the mid-40s to mid-50s.  6:40-8:20 am.

column47: My description of the location: ""24.2 miles N of junction Hwy 95 and Hobsonway Rd."" My description of the site itself. ""Read Parker 31
column50: Arizona State University
column51: PI Robert Ohmart). All 3 transects are screwbean mesquite (Prosopis pubescens). A few cottonwoods grow along 7A and 7B and there is a small copse of screwbean amongst the Pluchea at the end of Parker 31. This is where the cuckoo was heard. 7A and 7B are differentiated because their respective structure types differ - generally between 15' and 20' on A but 15' or lower on B. They all have some salt cedar (Tamarix) although not much on Parker 31. All have patches of Pluchea as well.... An absolutely beautiful day today. Clear and partly cloudy.""--Habitat: Screwbean Mesquite.--Temperature: 65-->85F; Wind: 0-5 mph; Cloud cover: 50-->30%. Other vertebrates noted: Sceloporus magister - 2; Neotoma albigula - 1 nest.

Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: 60-65F; Wind: 2-8 mph; Cloud cover: 15-->70%. Other vertebrates noted: None.--Found a dried up Oenothera deltoides in the wash; guessed that it had washed down from elsewhere. Some apparent pairing activity in Verdins. Lycium still growing.

Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. column48: Fairly quiet in the dead of summer. The young GHOW from my last 2 visits here (5/21 and 6/10) are still recognizable as immatures but much closer to adult plumage even than on 6/10. At least one pair of ATFL is still feeding young; young shrikes still about. A Red-tailed Hawk was seen on th east (north?) side of Hwy 95. Beautiful and pleasant day.--Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: 80-->90F; Wind: 0-->10 mph; Cloud cover: 30%. Other vertebrates noted: Cnemidophorus tigris - 1; Ammospermophilus leucurus - 2.

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Callisaurus draconoides - 5; Uta stansburiana - 10; Lepus californicus - 1; Odocoileus hemionus - tracks.--This wash may have run during the September 9-10
column48: 1977 rains but doesn't appear to have done so extensively. No significant visible damage. This was the only type V desert wash transect due to the size of the taller trees in the wash - the vegetation is very sparse compared to the type VI east side washes. Lycium dormant here (in contrast to the leafed out and flowering plants in the east side washes). Some of the smoke trees had put out a few blossoms that were just opening and Stephanomeria also in bloom.--Ash-throated Flycatchers have vacated these washes now.

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Dipodomys merriami - 1 female (dead in wash); Uta stansburiana - 5.--Very wet here - undoubtedly from the same storm front that I noted in the east side washes the previous evening. However
column50: here from rains in September. I noted Lycium leafing out in October here but almost every plant has lost most of those leaves or
column52: they have dried up. Only one plant had a few green leaves remaining. Found two individuals of Physalis crassifolia with fruit from flowers that bloomed in response to those rains
column53: however. The mistletoe berries were ""mostly new but a few are nearly ripe and the Phainopeplas are already eating them - only 1 Phainopepla was here on 10/9...""--I wondered if the D. merriami noted below had gotten wet and died from hypothermia overnight - maybe the wash did run or that animal's burrow got saturated somehow. There were no injuries evident on the animal. Saw loose flocks of feeding birds containing juncos

column48: also); Lycium brevipes (fruit also); Nicotiana trigonophylla. column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Lepus californicus - 1; Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--I noted the lack of any member of the sparrow guild and ground feeders - likely because the wash had run and washed all the seeds away. I also noted that I detected higher numbers of verdins and gnatcatchers than the previous month possibly because the birds are pairing up and are more vocal and visible. Also more Phainopeplas though they don't seem to be pairing yet. Some are giving a quiet twittery song.--I noted that this wash appeared to have run water within the last month although the last rain I could remember was on 6 November
column48: one day prior to my last visit to these transects. On that day I had noted  that the wash was quite wet but did not appear to have run. That day in December I was unable to find my footprints from 7 November and
column50: those prints would still have been there. I wondered if there'd been another storm in those mountains since that we'd not noticed in Ehrenberg. Whatever the case
column51: there had to have been some water in the wash as the Lycium in this wash which put out new growth in late September
column52: died back quickly between then and November
column53: but was now putting out much more new growth than it had in September.--Plant notes: Opuntia basillaris; O. rammosissima;Pectis papposa (blooming); Encelia frutescens; Coldenia plicata and Dalea emoryi over by the cliff edge; Atriplex polycarpa (with mature seed); Datura meteloides; Encelia farinosa; Euphorbia polycarpa; Euphorbia sp.; and Asclepias subulata (blooming); Hilaria rigida was found scattered amongst the adjacent creosote flats.

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: 55-->65F; Wind: 0-2 mph; Cloud cover: 0%. There are piles of freshly dropped leaves underneath all fo the ironwoods here though the trees do not show it. Strangely
column48: here as nowhere else I have seen locally
column49: the wash ran as a result of the winter rains. The sand appears wet and saturated still.""

The White-winged Doves were brownish-gray with dark malars. The eyes were red surrounded by pale blue feathering. The wing coverts were white and the primaries were black. The breast was paler brown than the back. The belly back to the undertail coverts were gray. The underside of the tail was black basally and clean white distally. The tail was square-shaped. All these markings differ from the Mourning Dove''s.
